# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geojson-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geojson-format/geojson] The features include points (therefore addresses and locations), line strings (therefore streets, highways and boundaries), polygons (countries, provinces, tracts of land), and multi-part collections of these types.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] GeoJSON features are not limited to representing entities of the physical world only; mobile routing and navigation apps, for example, might describe their service coverage using GeoJSON.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] The GeoJSON format differs from other geographic information system standards in that it was written and is maintained not by a formal standards organization, but by an Internet working group of developers.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] A notable offspring of GeoJSON is TopoJSON, an extension of GeoJSON that encodes geospatial topology and that typically provides smaller file sizes.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] The GeoJSON format working group and discussion were begun in March 2007 and the format specification was finalized in June 2008.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] In April 2015 the Internet Engineering Task Force founded the *Geographic JSON working group* which released GeoJSON as RFC 7946 in August 2016.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] They may be [longitude, latitude] or [eastings, northings].
[src:geojson-format/geojson] Elevation, in meters, is an optional third number.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] The coordinate reference system for all GeoJSON coordinates is a geographic coordinate reference system, using the World Geodetic System 1984 (WGS 84) [WGS84] datum, with longitude and latitude units of decimal degrees.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] An alternative to GeoJSON is to encode one geographic feature per line, with line breaks (or record-separator characters) designating the separation between records.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] This format can be much faster and more efficient to parse than normal GeoJSON, as tooling can read individual records in parallel.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] This format is similar to newline-delimited JSON.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] A reference implementation of the TopoJSON specification is available as a command-line tool to encode TopoJSON from GeoJSON (or ESRI Shapefiles) and a client side JavaScript library to decode TopoJSON back to GeoJSON again.
[src:geojson-format/geojson] TopoJSON is also supported by the popular OGR tool as of version 1.11 and PostGIS as of version 2.1.0.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The KML file specifies a set of features (place marks, images, polygons, 3D models, textual descriptions, etc.) that can be displayed on maps in geospatial software implementing the KML encoding.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] Every place has a longitude and a latitude.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] Other data can make a view more specific, such as tilt, heading, or altitude, which together define a "camera view" along with a timestamp or timespan.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] KML shares some of the same structural grammar as Geography Markup Language (GML).
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] Some KML information cannot be viewed in Google Maps or Mobile.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] KML files are very often distributed as **KMZ** files, which are zipped KML files with a .kmz extension.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The contents of a KMZ file are a single root KML document and optionally any overlays, images, icons, and COLLADA 3D models referenced in the KML including network-linked KML files.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The root KML document by convention is a file named "doc.kml" at the root directory level, which is the file loaded upon opening.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] By convention the root KML document is at root level and referenced files are in subdirectories (e.g. images for overlay).
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The MIME type associated with KML is *application/vnd.google-earth.kml+xml*; the MIME type associated with KMZ is *application/vnd.google-earth.kmz*.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] For its reference system, KML uses 3D geographic coordinates: longitude, latitude, and altitude, in that order, with negative values for west, south, and below mean sea level.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The longitude/latitude components (decimal degrees) are as defined by the World Geodetic System of 1984 (WGS84).
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] Altitude, the vertical component, is measured in meters from the WGS84 EGM96 Geoid vertical datum.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] If altitude is omitted from a coordinate string, e.g.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] (-77.03647, 38.89763) then the default value of 0 (approximately sea level) is assumed for the altitude component, i.e.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] A formal definition of the coordinate reference system (encoded as GML) used by KML is contained in the OGC KML 2.2 Specification.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] This definition references well-known EPSG CRS components.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The KML 2.2 specification was submitted to the Open Geospatial Consortium to assure its status as an open standard for all geobrowsers.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] In November 2007 a new KML 2.2 Standards Working Group was established within OGC to formalize KML 2.2 as an OGC standard.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] Comments were sought on the proposed standard until January 4, 2008, and it became an official OGC standard on April 14, 2008.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The OGC KML Standards Working Group finished working on change requests to KML 2.2 and incorporated accepted changes into the KML 2.3 standard.
[src:geojson-format/keyhole-markup-language] The official OGC KML 2.3 standard was published on August 4, 2015.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] The ISO 19125 standard comes in two parts.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] Part 1, ISO 19125-1 (SFA-CA for "common architecture"), defines a model for two-dimensional simple features, with linear interpolation between vertices, defined in a hierarchy of classes; this part also defines representation of geometry in text and binary forms.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] Part 2 of the standard, ISO 19125-2 (SFA-SQL), defines a "SQL/MM" language binding API for SQL under the prefix "ST_".
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] The open access OGC standards cover additionally APIs for CORBA and OLE/COM, although these have lagged behind the SQL one and are not standardized by ISO.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] There are also adaptations to other languages covered below.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] The geometries are associated with spatial reference systems.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] The standard also specifies attributes, methods and assertions with the geometries, in the object-oriented style.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] In general, a 2D geometry is simple if it contains no self-intersection.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] The specification defines DE-9IM spatial predicates and several spatial operators that can be used to generate new geometries from existing geometries.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] Part 2 is a SQL binding to Part 1, providing a translation of the interface to non-object-oriented environments.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] For example, instead of a `someGeometryObject.isEmpty()` as in Part 1, SQL/MM uses a `ST_IsEmpty(...)` function in SQL.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] The spatial extension adds the datatypes "Circularstring", "CompoundCurve", "CurvePolygon", "PolyhedralSurface", the last of which is also included into the OGC standard.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] It also defines the SQL/MM versions of these types and operations on them.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] GeoSPARQL is an OGC standard that is intended to allow geospatially-linked data representation and querying based on RDF and SPARQL by defining an ontology for geospatial reasoning supporting a small Simple Features (as well as DE-9IM and RCC8) RDFS/OWL vocabulary for GML and WKT literals.
[src:geojson-format/simple-features] As of 2012, various NoSQL databases had very limited support for "anything more complex than a bounding box or proximity search".
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] Coordinates for geometries may be 2D (*x*, *y*), 3D (*x*, *y*, *z*), 4D (*x*, *y*, *z*, *m*) with an *m* value that is part of a linear referencing system or 2D with an *m* value (*x*, *y*, *m*).
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] Three-dimensional geometries are designated by a "Z" after the geometry type and geometries with a linear referencing system have an "M" after the geometry type.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] Empty geometries that contain no coordinates can be specified by using the symbol `EMPTY` after the type name.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] WKT geometries are used throughout OGC specifications and are present in applications that implement these specifications.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] For example, PostGIS contains functions that can convert geometries to and from a WKT representation, making them human readable.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] The OGC standard definition requires a polygon to be topologically closed.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] It also states that if the exterior linear ring of a polygon is defined in a counterclockwise direction, then it will be seen from the "top".
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] Any interior linear rings should be defined in opposite fashion compared to the exterior ring, in this case, clockwise.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] Well-known binary (WKB) representations are typically shown in hexadecimal strings.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] Each data type has a unique data structure, such as the number of points or linear rings, followed by coordinates in 64-bit double numbers.
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] (SRID) and up to 4 ordinate values (XYZM).
[src:geojson-format/well-known-binary] It also supports circular curves, following elements named (but not fully defined) within the original WKT: CircularString, CompoundCurve, CurvePolygon and CompoundSurface.
